Update to previous forecasts. Increase to 99% for elapsed time and the impending vote anticipated for later today, 3 JAN 21, or soon thereafter. While many democrats voted for someone else in 2019, House Democrats are holding leadership elections as they grapple with unexpected losses and the prospects for a Congress that remains divided. The GOP appears likely to maintain control of the Senate. Plus House Republicans picked up at least eight seats, and several races are too close to call. It is likely that democrats will rally together to protect the influence of the party in the legislative branch. https://www.npr.org/2020/11/18/935718252/pelosi-set-to-be-reelected-speaker-despite-house-losses

If 11 do not show up and all Republkcans show then guess who wins? Also if Pelosi supporters stay away then a Democrat may be speaker but it won't be Pelosi. Pelosi always has opposition from within her party, would the opposition seize the moment to unseat her eve if means pjnishing party members who were sick or afraid to attend in person. https://thehill.com/homenews/house/530945-covid-19-could-complicate-pelosis-path-to-speaker-next-year How does this impact my 100% pelosi forecast? I am reducing by 10%. It is arbitrary, but i can't believe the Dem would be so dysfunctional as to allow a Republican speaker. Pelosi is intelligent and has demonstrated an abilith to keep the causus in line, but IF the opportjnity presented itself wouldn't progressives seize it?

"Speaker Nancy Pelosi had a blunt message for her junior members: I need your vote on Jan. 3 ... No one on Capitol Hill believes Pelosi is really at risk of losing the gavel. But the vote has become much more complicated with a shrunken Democratic majority and the coronavirus pandemic shadowing the proceedings ... According to House rules, Pelosi must win a majority of votes cast 'for a person by name' of the members who are in attendance and voting. So Pelosi can afford to allow a handful of her members to vote 'present,' but a vote for anyone else is more problematic ... At least two Democrats plan to vote against Pelosi on the floor: Reps. Conor Lamb of Pennsylvania and Jared Golden of Maine, according to several sources. A third, Rep. Abigail Spanberger of Virginia, could also vote 'no,' though she declined to comment in a recent interview ... A single Democrat forced to stay home because of an infection or quarantine period â€” not to mention other health issues â€” could upset Pelosiâ€™s careful balancing act." https://www.politico.com/news/2020/12/11/nancy-pelosi-speaker-vote-444409

To be elected speaker a candidate needs a majority of the votes cast, which currently is 218 votes in the 435 representatives of the House. There have only been a few instances where a person did not receive the majority of the full membership (last Boehner in 2015 but he still was elected with 216). The democrats held a 232 to 197 majority in the 116th Congress and waiting or dust to settle for the 117th Congress will still hold the majority. Although Pelosi had 15 people vote against her last time, a strong democratic unity platform is being pushed.
Democrats voted to keep her as their nominee as she ran unopposed, and full house vote will have the same outcome with Democratic control.

"Democrats in the US House of Representatives voted on Wednesday to keep House Speaker Nancy Pelosi in her job for another two years, despite the party losing seats to Republicans in the Nov. 3 election. The full House still must vote for speaker in early January, when Republicans will put up their own candidate for the job but are likely to lose since they will be in the minority in the 435-seat chamber." https://www.cnbctv18.com/politics/house-democrats-back-pelosi-for-another-term-as-speaker-7518241.htm

Base Rate: Over the past 120 years (60 congresses), there have been 25 changes in speakers. Of those, 11 have been because the party in power changed. The other 14 were within party changes.
